      "name": "t:sections.rich_text.presets.rich_text.name",
      "settings": {
        "width": "full-width",
        "title": "",
        "text": "<h2>Flood Lights That Turn Night Into a Work Zone Advantage</h2><p>When the job doesn’t stop at sunset, the right <strong>Flood lights</strong> are more than a convenience—they’re a safety upgrade. Whether you’re loading equipment, backing into a dark lot, working a roadside call, or setting up a perimeter at a job site, strong, wide-beam lighting helps you see hazards sooner and work with confidence.</p><p>That’s exactly what this collection is built for: dependable <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> and <strong>Scene Lighting</strong> options designed for real vehicles and real conditions—vibration, rain, dust, mud, and long shifts. If you need broad illumination that reduces shadows and improves awareness around your vehicle, you’re in the right place.</p><p>Below, you’ll find a clear guide to choosing the best <strong>Scene Lights</strong> and floods for your application—without blog fluff, and without overcomplicating it.</p><h2>What Flood Lights Do (and Why They Matter on Work Vehicles)</h2><p><strong>Flood lights</strong> are designed to spread light over a wide area rather than projecting a narrow beam far down the road. That wide pattern is the key: it improves visibility around your vehicle, reduces harsh shadows, and helps you spot obstacles, people, and equipment in your immediate work area.</p><p>They’re commonly used for:</p><ul><li>Loading and unloading tools or cargo.</li><li>Hookups and recoveries (tow, roadside service).</li><li>Job-site setup and teardown.</li><li>Nighttime repairs and inspections.</li><li>Backing, staging, and maneuvering in tight spaces.</li><li>Perimeter lighting for safety and awareness.</li></ul><p>In emergency support and work-truck environments, good <strong>Scene Lighting</strong> can reduce trip hazards, improve communication, and help crews stay visible and coordinated.</p><h2>Flood Lights vs. Scene Lights: What’s the Difference?</h2><p>You’ll often see “flood” and “scene” used together—and for good reason. Many <strong>Scene Lights</strong> are essentially wide-beam flood lights designed specifically for vehicle mounting and work-area illumination.</p><p>A simple way to think about it:</p><ul><li><strong>Flood lights:</strong> wide-beam lighting used for general area illumination.</li><li><strong>Scene Lighting:</strong> flood-style lighting placed strategically to illuminate a work zone around the vehicle (rear, side, or 360°).</li></ul><p>So if you’re building a dedicated work-zone setup—rear-facing for loading, side-facing for roadside work, or both—you’re looking for <strong>Scene Lights</strong> (usually LED floods built for that job).</p><h2>Where to Mount Flood Lights for Best Coverage</h2><p>Placement matters just as much as brightness. The best <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> are the ones aimed where you actually work.</p><h3>Rear-Facing Flood Lights</h3><p>Perfect for loading, hitching, hookups, and backing. Rear floods help you see obstacles behind the vehicle and reduce the “black hole” effect in dark lots or on unlit roads.</p><h3>Side-Facing Scene Lights</h3><p>Side-mounted <strong>Scene Lighting</strong> is a game-changer for roadside assistance, construction support, and utility work. It lights the work zone where people are walking, carrying tools, and moving around traffic.</p><h3>Roof, Rack, or High-Mount Applications</h3><p>Higher mounting points help spread light further and reduce shadows close to the vehicle. If you’re illuminating a broader perimeter, high-mounted floods can provide a more even wash.</p><h3>Bumper or Low-Mount Applications</h3><p>Lower mounts can be useful for close-range tasks, but they’re more exposed to debris, impacts, and road spray. If you mount low, durability and sealing become even more important.</p><p>To build a full vehicle lighting package, many customers pair floods with <strong>Work Lights</strong>, <strong>Backup Lights</strong>, and <strong>LED Light Bars</strong> for layered visibility and function.</p><h2>Choosing the Right LED Flood Lights for Your Job</h2><p>Not all <strong>floodlights</strong> are created equal. Here are the practical factors that matter when shopping for this collection.</p><h3>1) Beam Pattern and Coverage</h3><p>A true flood beam spreads light wide to cover the work area. If you’re lighting a scene (not the road), prioritize wide coverage and even distribution.</p><h3>2) Brightness (Useful Light, Not Just Numbers)</h3><p>Brightness specs can help compare products, but what you really want is effective illumination with minimal hotspots. A well-designed optic gives you a smoother spread—better for working and safer for nearby eyes.</p><h3>3) Durability and Weather Resistance</h3><p>Work vehicles live outside. Your <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> should be ready for:</p><ul><li>Rain, snow, and washdowns.</li><li>Dust and mud.</li><li>Vibration and constant movement.</li><li>Heat and long run times.</li></ul><h3>4) Mounting Hardware and Adjustability</h3><p>Solid brackets and secure mounting matter more than people expect. You want lights that stay aimed where you set them—especially on trucks that see rough roads.</p><h3>5) Power, Wiring, and Control</h3><p>Think about how you’ll run them:</p><ul><li>Will they be tied into reverse?</li><li>Controlled by a dedicated switch?</li><li>Activated as part of a scene lighting “mode”?</li></ul><p>If your vehicle runs multiple auxiliary lights, a clean control plan prevents messy wiring and makes daily use easier.</p><h2>Step-by-Step: How to Build a Simple Scene Lighting Setup</h2><p>This is a planning checklist (not an install manual) to help you select the right <strong>Scene Lights</strong> and avoid common mistakes.</p><h3>Step 1: Identify Your Work Zones</h3><p>Where do you actually need light—rear, driver side, passenger side, or all around? Most users start with rear floods and add side lighting if they work near traffic.</p><h3>Step 2: Choose Mounting Locations</h3><p>Pick mounting points that give a clear light path and protect the fixtures where possible (rack crossbars, rear doors, headache racks, side toolboxes).</p><h3>Step 3: Select the Right Beam and Quantity</h3><p>One light might be enough for a small rear work zone. Larger vehicles and wider work areas often benefit from multiple floods spaced for even coverage.</p><h3>Step 4: Plan Controls</h3><p>Decide whether you want:</p><ul><li>A single scene lighting switch.</li><li>Separate switches for the rear and sides.</li><li>Automatic activation (like reverse-triggered rear floods).</li></ul><h3>Step 5: Add Redundancy Where Needed</h3><p>If your work is high-risk (highway shoulder, busy lots), consider layered lighting: <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> for the work area plus <strong>Warning Lights</strong> for visibility to other drivers.</p><h2>Scene Lighting for Different Vehicles and Industries</h2><p><strong>Tow & roadside service:</strong> Rear and side floods help with hookups, winching, and working around the vehicle safely.<br/> <strong>Utility & telecom:</strong> Side-facing <strong>Scene Lighting</strong> supports bucket work, inspections, and night repairs.<br/> <strong>Construction support:</strong> Wide floods illuminate staging areas and improve crew coordination.<br/> <strong>Emergency support & command:</strong> <strong>Scene Lights</strong> create a safer perimeter and improve visibility for responders and equipment.<br/> <strong>Delivery & service vans:</strong> Rear floods reduce trip hazards during nighttime loading and stops.</p><p>No matter the industry, the goal is the same: reduce shadows, improve awareness, and make the workspace safer.</p><h2>What to Look For in High-Quality Flood Lights</h2><p>When you’re investing in <strong>Flood lights</strong>, you’re investing in uptime. The best options are the ones that keep working through weather, vibration, and long runs.</p><p>Prioritize:</p><ul><li>Sealed housings and quality construction.</li><li>Strong brackets and hardware.</li><li>Even beam spread for practical working visibility.</li><li>Reliable performance in heat and harsh conditions.</li><li>Clean integration with your vehicle’s electrical setup.</li></ul><p>If you’re not sure where to start, a straightforward setup is rear-facing <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> for loading, plus one or two side-facing <strong>Scene Lights</strong> for the primary work side of your vehicle.</p>",
        "heading_size": "medium",
        "text_alignment": "left"
      }
    },
    "dynamic_rich_text_L8RbH8": {
      "type": "dynamic-rich-text",
