      "settings": {
        "width": "full-width",
        "title": "",
        "text": "<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>1) What are floodlights used for on vehicles?</h3><p><strong>Flood lights</strong> provide wide-area illumination around a vehicle for loading, repairs, backing, and job-site work. They’re designed to reduce shadows and improve close-range visibility.</p><h3>2) What is scene lighting?</h3><p><strong>Scene Lighting</strong> refers to lighting placed to illuminate a work zone around the vehicle—often rear-facing for loading and side-facing for roadside or job-site tasks. Many scene lights are wide-beam LED floods designed for vehicle mounting.</p><h3>3) Are LED flood lights better than halogen for work lighting?</h3><p>In most vehicle applications, <strong>LED Flood Lights</strong> are preferred because they’re efficient, bright, and durable, with strong output for long runtimes. The best choice still depends on your vehicle and wiring setup.</p><h3>4) Where should I mount scene lights on a truck?</h3><p>Common placements include rear-facing mounts for loading/hitching and side-facing mounts for illuminating the work area next to the vehicle. Higher mounting points often spread light more evenly and reduce shadows.</p><h3>5) How many scene lights do I need?</h3><p>It depends on the size of your vehicle and the area you want to illuminate. Some setups use a single rear flood, while larger trucks and wider work zones may need multiple <strong>Scene Lights</strong> spaced for even coverage.</p>",
        "heading_size": "medium",
        "text_alignment": "left"
      }
